Shubham Chaudhary: The format string '%(asctime)s %(levelname)s %(message)s' specifies three placeholders separated by spaces:

Jaideep: while printing 5/2 , if any one is made float by doing 5.0/2 than in second case both 5.0 and 2.0 are treated as float , so similarly if we are doing the same with one data type as float and other as double than will the compiler treat both of them as double (that is the larger data type)? Jaideep: yes Shubham Chaudhary: ok Shubham Chaudhary: Yes, in C and C++, if you perform an arithmetic operation between a float and a double, the compiler will promote the float to a double before performing the operation. This is because double has a higher precision than float and can represent larger and more precise numbers. Shubham Chaudhary: ex: Shubham Chaudhary: float a = 5.0f;
double b = 2.0;
double c = a + b;
Shubham Chaudhary: The compiler will promote the float value of a to a double before adding it to b, and the result will be stored in the double variable c. Jaideep: also if instead of writing number if we store than number in a variable than will it work? Shubham Chaudhary: yes
Shubham Chaudhary: wait
Shubham Chaudhary: The yield keyword in Python is used in generator functions to create a generator object. A generator is a type of iterator that can be iterated over using a for loop or by calling the next() function on the generator object.
Shubham Chaudhary: When a generator function is called, it returns a generator object without executing the function's body. The body of the function is executed only when the generator's next() method is called. When the yield keyword is encountered in the function, the current value of the expression after the yield is returned by the next() method, and the function's execution is paused at that point.
Shubham Chaudhary: So, while yield and return are both used to return values from a function, they have different uses and behaviors. yield is used to create a generator, while return is used to exit a function and return a value to the caller.

global and local variables MONU: scope* MONU: ?? Shubham Chaudhary: in c++ Shubham Chaudhary: ? Shubham Chaudhary: In C++, a variable's scope determines its accessibility within a program. A variable can be either a global variable or a local variable.

A global variable is declared outside of any function, and it can be accessed from any part of the program. A global variable is initialized once, and its value remains the same throughout the program. Global variables can be declared using the extern keyword in a header file and defined in a source file.

For example: Shubham Chaudhary: // Global variable
int g_var = 10;

int main() {
// Access global variable
std::cout << "Global variable value: " << g_var << std::endl;
return 0;
}
Shubham Chaudhary: A local variable is declared inside a function or a block, and it can only be accessed within that function or block. A local variable is initialized every time the function or block is called, and its value is not retained between function calls. Shubham Chaudhary: int main() {
// Local variable
int l_var = 20;
std::cout << "Local variable value: " << l_var << std::endl;
return 0;
}
Shubham Chaudhary: In general, it is good practice to use local variables when possible to avoid name clashes and improve code clarity. However, global variables can be useful in certain situations, such as when multiple functions need to share data or when constants need to be defined. Shubham Chaudhary: read

Monika: what is bias and variance
Monika: and difference between them ???
Shubham Chaudhary: The difference between bias and variance is that bias measures the error introduced by approximating a real-life problem with a simplified model, while variance measures the variability of the model's predictions for different training sets. In general, there is a trade-off between bias and variance in model building. A model with high bias tends to have low variance, while a model with low bias tends to have high variance.

Ankit: what is sample data and population data Shubham Chaudhary: Population data refers to data that includes every member of a particular group or population being studied. For example, if you wanted to know the average height of all people in the United States, you would need to collect data on every single person living in the United States. This would be considered population data.

Sample data, on the other hand, refers to a subset of the population data that is used to make inferences about the population as a whole. In our example of studying the average height of people in the United States, it would be impractical to collect data on every single person, so we might instead collect data on a smaller group of people, such as 1,000 randomly selected individuals.
